lab:
1. Create a new pod using the nginx image.
A: kubectl run nginx --image=nginx

2. Create a new pod with the name redis and the image redis123.
Utilize a pod-definition YAML file. Please note that the image name redis123 is intentionally incorrect. Do NOT correct the image at this stage; you will address this in the subsequent task.
A: can be done just by 'kubectl run redis --image=redis123'; if we want to generte a yaml file, we add '--dry-run=client -o yaml'; add a name '> redis-definition.yaml'
We use kubectl run command with --dry-run=client -o yaml option to create a manifest file :-
kubectl run redis --image=redis123 --dry-run=client -o yaml > redis-definition.yaml
After that, using kubectl create -f command to create a resource from the manifest file :-  //create a pod using the yaml file
kubectl create -f redis-definition.yaml 
Verify the work by running kubectl get command :-
kubectl get pods

3. Now change the image on this pod to redis.
Once done, the pod should be in a running state.
A: 
cat redis-definition.yaml
vi redis-definition.yaml  //edit the file
kubectl apply -f redis-definition.yaml   //apply the changes


very important difference of using --dry-run=client
case 1: 
k run <pod-name> --image=nginx --dry-run=client -o yaml > <file-name>.yaml
k create -f <file-name>.yaml    
which means that if use --dry-run=client, the pod is not created actually
case 2:
k run <pod-name> --image=nginx -o yaml > <file-name>.yaml
k replace --force -f <file-name>.yaml
the pod is created if not use --dry-run=client
note: the --dry-run=client flag in Kubernetes kubectl commands simulates the execution of a command and outputs the result without actually sending it to 
the Kubernetes API server or making any changes to the cluster.


